expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>3081</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00IE</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00IE.xml</fr:route><fr:title><fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">Relations</fr:link> in databases</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We now come to an example of a <fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">relation between multiple sets</fr:link>: we could define a relation <fr:tex>R \subseteq   \text {Movies} \times \text {Directors} \times \text {Years} \times \text {People}</fr:tex> consisting of tuples <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( m,d,y,p \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> where <fr:tex>m</fr:tex> is a movie directed by <fr:tex>d</fr:tex> in year <fr:tex>y</fr:tex> with <fr:tex>p</fr:tex> as a cast member.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:context><fr:related><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="true"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>6298</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00I7</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00I7.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Relation</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:em><fr:strong>(binary) relation</fr:strong></fr:em> <fr:tex>R</fr:tex> from a set <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> to a set <fr:tex>B</fr:tex>, written <fr:tex>R \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  B</fr:tex> or <fr:tex>R \in   \mathrm {Rel} { \mathopen {} \left ( A,B \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> is defined to be a subset <fr:tex>R \subseteq  A \times  B</fr:tex>. We shall typically write <fr:tex>a \mathrel {R}b</fr:tex> for <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( a,b \right ) \mathclose {}} \in  R</fr:tex>. More generally, a <fr:em><fr:strong>relation between multiple sets</fr:strong></fr:em> <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( A_i \right ) \mathclose {}} _{i \in  I}</fr:tex> is defined to be a subset of the cartesian product <fr:tex>\prod _{i \in  I} A_i</fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:related><fr:backlinks><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
