root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>3093</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00II</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00II.xml</fr:route><fr:title>The identity <fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">relation</fr:link></fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For any set <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>, we can form the <fr:em><fr:strong>identity <fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">relation</fr:link></fr:strong></fr:em> <fr:tex>\mathsf {id}_{ A } \colon  A \mathbin { \nrightarrow }  A</fr:tex>, also called the <fr:em><fr:strong>equality <fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I7">relation</fr:link></fr:strong></fr:em>, which relates each element of <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> to itself. In other words, we have <fr:tex>a \mathrel { \mathsf {id}_{ A } } a'</fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex>a=a'</fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:p>We have already seen the <fr:link
href="jms-00I9.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00I9">square root relation from positive reals to reals</fr:link>, which corresponds to a <fr:em>total</fr:em> but <fr:em>many-valued</fr:em> function. We can define an analogous relationship in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00IJ"
href="jms-00IJ.xml"
taxon="Example"></fr:ref> below from positive integers (naturals) to integers, which will correspond to a <fr:em>partial</fr:em> and many-valued function.</fr:p><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
